                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The stone is inscribed with an Ogham inscription running vertically along the left edge of the stone, reading upwards. The stone also has a Roman-letter inscription in two lines, reading vertically downwards. The stone was later inverted and reused for a cross-carving so inscriptions are inverted in current display as is also seen in B41 and B42 (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 242-4). Nash-Williams (1950, 81) described the cross as <q>'a <rs type="decoration">linear Latin ring-cross</rs> incised on the new head, partly overriding the tip of two of the end-letters in l. 2 of the Latin inscription'</q></layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The Roman-letter inscription is in <q>light Roman capitals with one minuscule F and two 'gate' forms of N...in this inscription the C is beginning to become angular; the two Ns, one abot the other, of the repeated element CUNO, show a standard capital above and a 'gate' N below. The dating of the first half of the sixth century suggests that the range of written forms was widening during this century to extend the range of letters thought suitable for monumental use</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 242).
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
